            <pb n="714" facs="#f0001"/>
            <milestone unit="section" rendition="#hr"/>
            <lb break="yes"/>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="#k">Prussia.</hi>&#x2014;<hi rendition="#i">Von
                Humboldt.</hi>&#x2014;The <hi rendition="#i">Prussian Universal<lb break="yes"
                    />Gazette</hi> publishes the following letter:&#x2014;&#x201C;Whenever I<lb
                    break="yes"/>find my name quoted in an unfavourable manner, either in<lb
                    break="yes"/>a political or literary point of view, in the journals, I make<lb
                    break="yes"/>it a point to remain silent; but I break through that<lb
                    break="yes"/>rule when any calumny is directed against one of my<lb break="yes"
                />intimate friends. The <hi rendition="#i">Mannheim Gazette</hi> of the 28th ult.<lb
                    break="yes"/>announces the following under the head Berlin:&#x2014;&#x2018;We<lb
                    break="yes"/>have been informed that M. Arago has declined to accept<lb
                    break="yes"/>the Prussian Order of Merit, and has sent it back. This<lb
                    break="yes"/>report has been confirmed, and M. Arago has written on<lb
                    break="yes"/>the subject to Alexander Von Humboldt.&#x2019; This statement<lb
                    break="yes"/>is as ridiculous as it is absurd. The King of Prussia,<lb
                    break="yes"/>after conferring the Order of Merit on a number of per-<lb
                    break="no"/>
                <pb n="715" facs="#f0002"/>
                <cb/> sons unconnected with the Army, simultaneously appointed<lb break="yes"
                />Knights of that Order M. Arago, M. Letronne, M. de<lb break="yes"/>Chateaubriand,
                M. Daguerre, M. Ingrès, M. Horace<lb break="yes"/>Vernet, and M. Guy-Lussac. M.
                Arago was the first who<lb break="yes"/>replied, on the 8th of June, 1842, that he
                accepted the<lb break="yes"/>decoration. He wrote to me to that effect, in my
                    capacity<lb break="yes"/>of Chancellor of the new institution, and expressed
                    himself<lb break="yes"/>in terms which bespoke his satisfaction.</p>
            <lb break="yes"/>
            <dateline>&#x201C;Berlin, Nov. 1, 1843.</dateline>
            <closer>
                <salute>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Alexander Von Humboldt.&#x201D;</hi>
                </salute>
            </closer>
            <lb break="yes"/>
